  "text": "Firefox's multi-process (Fission) architecture manages content process lifecycle through several key classes in the dom/ipc directory:\n\n1. **ContentParent** (dom/ipc/ContentParent.h/.cpp): The parent-side manager for a content process. This is a final class that inherits from PContentParent and manages the main IPC communication channel with a single content process. It handles process creation, shutdown, memory reporting, and coordination with the parent process.\n\n2. **ContentProcessManager** (dom/ipc/ContentProcessManager.h/.cpp): A singleton registry that tracks all active content processes and browser tabs. It maintains mappings between ContentParent instances and their IDs, and registers/unregisters BrowserParent (tab) objects. This class provides centralized access to any content process by ID.\n\n3. **BrowserParent** (dom/ipc/BrowserParent.h/.cpp): The parent-side representation of a remote browser tab. A final class inheriting from PBrowserParent, it manages IPC communication for a single tab running in a content process. Each BrowserParent is registered with ContentProcessManager and communicates with its corresponding BrowserChild in the content process.\n\n4. **PreallocatedProcessManager** (dom/ipc/PreallocatedProcessManager.h/.cpp): A pool manager that preallocates a ContentParent in advance to improve spawn time when new content processes are needed. It respects the dom.ipc.processPrelaunch.enabled preference and maintains a ready-to-use ContentParent that can be claimed via Take() to speed up content process allocation.\n\nThese components form the core of Firefox's process management system, where ContentParent manages individual processes, ContentProcessManager provides registry access, BrowserParent represents individual tabs, and PreallocatedProcessManager optimizes process creation latency."
